votes.recommendedFix:
Add a helper mirroring completeRun's pod cull and call it at every site that drives a run terminal and closes its leases:

func (c *RunController) removeAllRunPods(run *v1.Run) {
    kept := c.State.Pods[:0]
    for _, pod := range c.State.Pods {
        if pod.Namespace == run.Namespace && pod.Labels[binder.LabelRunName] == run.Name {
            continue
        }
        kept = append(kept, pod)
    }
    c.State.Pods = kept
}

Call c.removeAllRunPods(run) immediately after closeRunLeases in (1) failRun, (2) HandleNodeFailure's post-loop `for runKey, phase := range phases { if phase == RunPhaseFailed ...}` sweep, and (3) applyResolution's resolver-cut `default: run.Status.Phase = RunPhaseFailed` branch. Do NOT add it to failGroupWithoutSpare's checkpoint-grace (Pending) branch — that half-plane is legal and bounded by CheckpointDeadline. For defence in depth, guard the sweep-site call on run.Status.CheckpointDeadline == nil so the exemption keys on the deadline, not the phase, as the finding advises. This makes the two planes agree: a terminal run releases both its ledger and its pods, so the GPUs it hands back are actually free.

